You can use `ssize_t`. You should always use `size_t` or `ssize_t` types when dealing with lengths/sizes of memory. They are not the same thing as `unsigned int` or `int` on 64bit systems:

```
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    printf("unsigned int: %u\nint: %u\nsize_t: %u\nssize_t: %u\n",sizeof(unsigned int),sizeof(int),sizeof(size_t),sizeof(ssize_t));
    return 0;
}

unsigned int: 4
int: 4
size_t: 8
ssize_t: 8
```

